            . I live in <placeName id="t18310407-227-crimeloc1219">Chapel-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18310407-227-crimeloc1219" type="placeName" value="Chapel-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18310407-227-crimeloc1219" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310407-227-off1217 t18310407-227-crimeloc1219"></join>, just opposite Mr. Puttock's. On the 22nd of March, about five o'clock, I saw the prisoner looking in at the window - I saw him snatch an apron off the eggs in the shop, and run away; I saw him running, but could not catch him - I had seen him several times before, and knew him perfectly well; I saw him in custody the next day.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310407-227-person1613">
                  CHARLES 
                  CLARK
               <interp inst="t18310407-227-person1613" type="surname" value="CLARK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-227-person1613" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-227-person1613" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I apprehended the prisoner in a yard, among a parcel of boys - I knew him well by the description given of him; when he saw me he ran into a house, and tried to hide himself - I took him, and he said,"What do you want?" I said, "You will soon know," and as we went along he said, "I know nothing about the apron;" I had not mentioned an apron.</p>
               <p>PETER PUTTOCK. I was at home, and missed the apron, but did not see it taken.</p>
